\section{Appendix Extension: Detailed Results and Reproducibility (Iteration 1)}
\label{app:extension-1}

\subsection{Detailed Results and Data}
The saved scan spans 51 evenly spaced idle times over $[0, 2 t_{\pi}]$, or $[0, \SI{352.112676}{\nano\second}]$. The analytic trace and the two framework-backed traces agree pointwise at the plotted resolution, so the single figure is sufficient to summarize the full dataset for this probe. Table~\ref{tab:extension-summary} records the compact numerical digest that supports the report claims.

\begin{table}[h]
\caption{Compact numerical digest for the validated probe.}
\label{tab:extension-summary}
\begin{tabular}{ll}
\toprule
Quantity & Value \\
\midrule
First positive $\pi$ crossing & \SI{176.056338}{\nano\second} \\
Maximum wrapped analytic mismatch & $8.882\times 10^{-16}\,\mathrm{rad}$ \\
Maximum wrapped truncation difference & $0\,\mathrm{rad}$ \\
Measured runtime & \SI{1.12}{\second} \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\subsection{Reproducibility}
\subsubsection{Modeling and Simulation Assumptions}
The calculation uses a two-level qubit, cavity truncations of 2 and 3 Fock states, closed-system evolution, and the first-order dispersive convention in which the excited-branch phase shift is proportional to photon number. The comparison quantity is the wrapped relative phase modulo $2\pi$.

\subsubsection{Reproduction Procedure}
\begin{enumerate}
	\item From the study root, run \path{python scripts/free_dispersive_pi_probe.py}.
	\item Confirm that the script writes one CSV file, one JSON artifact, and one dual-format figure, and that it reports the first positive $\pi$ crossing near \SI{176.056338}{\nano\second}.
	\item Open \path{scripts/reproducibility_notebook.ipynb} for the fast load-first walkthrough and optional commented rerun path.
\end{enumerate}

